  "prompt": "What is colour of water?",
  "response": "In small quantities, water appears colorless to the human eye. However, when observed in large volumes, water can take on a slight blue tint. This blue color is due to the absorption of light in the red part of the visible spectrum by water molecules. The effect is more noticeable in large bodies of water, such as oceans or lakes, where the depth and the volume of water enhance the blue appearance. \n\nAdditionally, reflective properties and the presence of impurities, algae, or other substances can alter the perceived color of water in different environments. For example, water in rivers or ponds might appear greenish due to plant life or yellowish/brownish if it contains dissolved organic matter.",
